Academy. And without further ado, I would like to invite Dr.

24
00:01:20.060 --> 00:01:21.200
Sun to the stage.

25
00:01:27.740 --> 00:01:31.520
Well, thank you so much, Ruben, for organizing this important

26
00:01:31.620 --> 00:01:35.400
session and for giving me the opportunity to present our

27
00:01:35.460 --> 00:01:39.160
work on long-term survivors of pediatric cancer.

28
00:01:40.560 --> 00:01:41.740
I have--

29
00:01:42.580 --> 00:01:43.000
Okay, see.

30
00:01:44.280 --> 00:01:47.840
Somehow it does not work. Okay. I have nothing to

31
00:01:47.880 --> 00:01:48.520
disclose.

32
00:01:49.640 --> 00:01:53.580
So for those of us involved in pediatric cancer research,

33
00:01:54.240 --> 00:01:57.980
cure of the cancer is not the only goal as we have to be concerned

34
00:01:58.060 --> 00:02:01.680
about the adverse outcomes that happen in long-term survivors

35
00:02:01.860 --> 00:02:05.480
of pediatric cancer. Therefore, in this study,

36
00:02:05.900 --> 00:02:09.720
we are studying, looking at the genomic toxicity using

37
00:02:09.801 --> 00:02:13.780
materials collected from adult survivors of pediatric

38
00:02:13.800 --> 00:02:14.299
cancer.

39
00:02:15.300 --> 00:02:15.640
So,

40
00:02:16.480 --> 00:02:20.180
the technique we use for evaluating genomic toxicity

41
00:02:20.380 --> 00:02:22.540
is mutational signature analysis.

42
00:02:23.060 --> 00:02:27.040
Many people here already know what it is, but I just want to give a little brief

43
00:02:27.100 --> 00:02:30.880
introduction so that those who are not familiar with the analytical process

44
00:02:31.480 --> 00:02:31.920
can

45
00:02:33.160 --> 00:02:37.040
get familiar with this. So basically, what

46
00:02:37.100 --> 00:02:40.780
we do is using 96 signature features

47
00:02:41.360 --> 00:02:45.250
based on the mutant site, as well as one base pair

48
00:02:45.320 --> 00:02:48.900
flanking regions, to look into the profiles like this,

49
00:02:49.400 --> 00:02:53.060
looking at the peaks and the spectrums to

50
00:02:53.120 --> 00:02:56.100
associate these imprinting pattern with

51
00:02:56.960 --> 00:02:59.400
either specific exposure or etiology.

52
00:02:59.790 --> 00:03:03.680
And what I'm showing here is actually a mutational signature

53
00:03:03.740 --> 00:03:05.420
we discovered from

54
00:03:06.460 --> 00:03:09.840
related to thiopurine treatment that leading to

55
00:03:09.960 --> 00:03:13.880
relapsed ALs a few years ago. So within

56
00:03:14.560 --> 00:03:18.420
cancer patients or individuals, the genomes of the mutations actually was

57
00:03:18.540 --> 00:03:22.080
contributed by a multitude of

58
00:03:22.120 --> 00:03:24.520
different mutational mechanisms.

59
00:03:24.580 --> 00:03:28.310
So we always use a signature extraction to deconvolute these

60
00:03:28.560 --> 00:03:29.640
different contributors

61
00:03:31.480 --> 00:03:34.000
that kind of shape the genome of an individual.

62
00:03:35.620 --> 00:03:39.530
So our journey started by looking into clonal hematopoiesis in the

63
00:03:39.600 --> 00:03:40.200
survivors,

64
00:03:41.200 --> 00:03:42.260
using the blood sample.

65
00:03:43.920 --> 00:03:47.180
Clonal hematopoiesis refers to acquisition of

66
00:03:47.240 --> 00:03:51.060
mutations in hematopoietic stem cells, leading to

67
00:03:51.100 --> 00:03:54.250
clonal expansion that can cause AML or

68
00:03:54.380 --> 00:03:57.900
cardiovascular disease. In pediatric cancer survivors,

69
00:03:58.460 --> 00:04:00.560
there is accelerated aging and

70
00:04:01.860 --> 00:04:05.380
clonal hematopoiesis is also a very well-defined aging biomarker.

71
00:04:05.769 --> 00:04:09.520
And this is a study published a few years ago, led by

72
00:04:09.540 --> 00:04:11.240
Kohei Hagiwara, a

73
00:04:12.060 --> 00:04:15.340
postdoc fellow then in my lab. So we used the St.

74
00:04:15.380 --> 00:04:19.101
Jude LIFE cohort that comprised of about 3,000

75
00:04:19.221 --> 00:04:22.900
survivors and 3,300 age-matched

76
00:04:23.020 --> 00:04:26.860
controls. We performed deep targeted sequencing and

77
00:04:26.880 --> 00:04:30.780
built up a statistical model to infer what is age-related versus

78
00:04:30.820 --> 00:04:32.880
therapy-related clonal hematopoiesis.

79
00:04:33.580 --> 00:04:37.460
Through this study, we found accelerated CH in the survivors

80
00:04:37.520 --> 00:04:41.440
compared with normal controls. We also discovered therapy-related

81
00:04:41.600 --> 00:04:45.160
STAT3 hotspot mutations that were highly enriched in

82
00:04:45.200 --> 00:04:46.940
Hodgkin lymphoma survivors.

83
00:04:48.680 --> 00:04:52.430
So to delineate what cell types were involved in

84
00:04:52.700 --> 00:04:53.110
these

85
00:04:54.040 --> 00:04:57.880
CH mutations, we used a platform, which

86
00:04:57.940 --> 00:05:01.720
is called Tapestry, that allow us to profile

87
00:05:02.200 --> 00:05:03.760
mutations along with

88
00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:08.480
an antibody panel for cell type classification

89
00:05:08.840 --> 00:05:12.280
at the single-cell level. And this is a work led by

90
00:05:12.740 --> 00:05:16.360
Siva in our genomic laboratory. So for the study, we

91
00:05:16.400 --> 00:05:20.280
profiled three Hodgkin lymphoma survivors, the blood cells,

92
00:05:20.740 --> 00:05:24.620
and we discovered that mutant cells, which are shown in these red dots here,

93
00:05:24.700 --> 00:05:28.240
appear to be highly enriched in the green cells,

94
00:05:28.680 --> 00:05:29.240
that were

95
00:05:30.040 --> 00:05:33.780
clustered based on the cell surface markers and shown to be

96
00:05:33.960 --> 00:05:35.980
CD4, CD8 T cells.

97
00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:40.840
So, we were looking for the enrichment mutations in these

98
00:05:40.860 --> 00:05:44.520
cell types and found there's a three to tenfold enrichment compared

99
00:05:44.660 --> 00:05:48.564
with the whole blood samples we analyzed.So

100
00:05:48.584 --> 00:05:52.294
from the three base pair sequencing context, we noted that

101
00:05:52.544 --> 00:05:52.924
these

102
00:05:54.264 --> 00:05:57.664
spectrums actually resemble a mutational signature called

103
00:05:57.804 --> 00:05:59.164
SBS25

104
00:06:00.084 --> 00:06:03.164
by COSMIC. And this

105
00:06:03.244 --> 00:06:07.204
SBS25, there is emerging evidence to show that it's associated

106
00:06:07.244 --> 00:06:08.904
with procapsid exposure

107
00:06:10.024 --> 00:06:13.964
that was used for treating Hodgkin lymphoma patients.

108
00:06:14.624 --> 00:06:16.344
So we performed whole genome

109
00:06:17.924 --> 00:06:20.684
single-cell sequencing and using the bulk

110
00:06:20.803 --> 00:06:24.484
sample as a

111
00:06:24.504 --> 00:06:27.554
control. And we were able to find most of

112
00:06:27.584 --> 00:06:31.444
the STAT3 mutant cells were only solely

113
00:06:31.524 --> 00:06:34.484
comprised with SBS25 signature, while

114
00:06:34.544 --> 00:06:38.184
the wild type cells have an admix of

115
00:06:38.224 --> 00:06:42.044
different signatures. And you can look at the spectrum

116
00:06:42.104 --> 00:06:45.744
differences, and under this mutagenesis background, the

117
00:06:45.784 --> 00:06:49.764
STAT3 mutation almost have 100% confidence to be

118
00:06:49.824 --> 00:06:53.784
caused by SBS25,

119
00:06:54.084 --> 00:06:57.044
linking them to procapsid exposure.

120
00:06:58.384 --> 00:07:01.964
So for this published study, we only analyzed three Hodgkin

121
00:07:01.984 --> 00:07:02.644
lymphoma

122
00:07:03.584 --> 00:07:07.324
survivors with one mutations, and we have later expanded

123
00:07:07.344 --> 00:07:11.124
this analysis to over 100

124
00:07:11.204 --> 00:07:14.824
CH positive survivors, and this is a study that was led

125
00:07:14.964 --> 00:07:18.424
by Siva and Nadia in my lab. She's here, and she will be

126
00:07:18.464 --> 00:07:22.444
presenting her poster on Tuesday morning, and you will hear more

127
00:07:22.504 --> 00:07:24.424
about the details of this analysis.

128
00:07:25.084 --> 00:07:28.554
So just to highlight some interesting findings, what we found, different

129
00:07:28.554 --> 00:07:32.304
mutations actually contribute to enrichment in

130
00:07:32.344 --> 00:07:35.404
different cell types. And this is an example that shows the

131
00:07:35.424 --> 00:07:38.704
DNMT3A mutations in 19 survivors.

132
00:07:39.204 --> 00:07:42.664
Some of them were highly enriched in monocytes, and some of them were

133
00:07:42.784 --> 00:07:46.604
enriched in double negative CD3+

134
00:07:46.644 --> 00:07:47.284
T cells.

135
00:07:48.764 --> 00:07:52.184
We were also to follow whether the mutational enrichment pattern

136
00:07:52.244 --> 00:07:52.944
persisted

137
00:07:54.284 --> 00:07:58.004
longitudinally using serial samples collected from the survivors.

138
00:07:58.583 --> 00:08:01.984
And this is the result from one of the Hodgkin lymphoma

139
00:08:02.384 --> 00:08:03.644
survivors that have the

140
00:08:04.684 --> 00:08:08.384
STAT3 mutation, and we have marked the

141
00:08:08.424 --> 00:08:12.104
mutant cells similarly, and also to the cell types

142
00:08:12.604 --> 00:08:15.984
in orange, the color for our

143
00:08:16.124 --> 00:08:16.764
CD8

144
00:08:18.224 --> 00:08:21.024
T cells, and shows that the

145
00:08:21.064 --> 00:08:25.044
enrichment happens at the age of

146
00:08:25.104 --> 00:08:28.964
47, and the same pattern was also found

147
00:08:29.504 --> 00:08:31.944
at the age of 49 and age of

148
00:08:32.164 --> 00:08:35.904
51 years old. So this is a pattern

149
00:08:35.944 --> 00:08:39.264
that carries through persistently throughout

150
00:08:41.064 --> 00:08:41.485
life.

151
00:08:42.605 --> 00:08:44.544
Oops. Don't know why I'm...

152
00:08:48.744 --> 00:08:52.644
All right. I'm sorry for not hitting the right button.

153
00:08:53.784 --> 00:08:54.104
So,

154
00:08:55.224 --> 00:08:59.184
knowing the cell type only reveals part of a story.

155
00:08:59.244 --> 00:09:02.504
What we really want to see is how the mutations impact

156
00:09:02.514 --> 00:09:06.334
the cell function. So to do this, what

157
00:09:06.384 --> 00:09:10.304
we figure out using whole genome transcriptome

158
00:09:10.404 --> 00:09:12.744
sequencing by full-length

159
00:09:14.404 --> 00:09:18.254
RNA-Seq may give us both the mutation status as

