00:29:50.608 --> 00:29:54.528
So our second speaker is Dr. Sam Benatti of the Wellcome

523
00:29:54.988 --> 00:29:58.768
Sanger Institute, who recently was announced as the new head of the Department

524
00:29:58.948 --> 00:30:02.868
of Pediatrics at the University of Cambridge and director of the Cambridge Children

525
00:30:02.988 --> 00:30:03.908
Research Institute.

526
00:30:05.008 --> 00:30:08.968
And Sam or Dr. Benatti will present his work on

527
00:30:09.208 --> 00:30:12.808
liver-specific platinum mutagenesis in children using duplex sequencing.

528
00:30:12.868 --> 00:30:13.368
So Sam.

529
00:30:17.368 --> 00:30:18.988
Thank you, Ruben, for

530
00:30:19.808 --> 00:30:21.848
inviting me. It's a real joy to be here.

531
00:30:24.008 --> 00:30:24.188
So

532
00:30:25.752 --> 00:30:29.552
I'm going to talk a little bit more about the field to give a bit

533
00:30:29.692 --> 00:30:33.552
more perhaps of an introduction. I'll talk about the experiment and our

534
00:30:33.652 --> 00:30:35.852
data and then conclude on a couple of things.

535
00:30:36.632 --> 00:30:36.892
So

536
00:30:37.952 --> 00:30:41.092
I try very hard not to study mutational signatures, but

537
00:30:41.751 --> 00:30:44.712
it's quite difficult not to when one is interested in genomics.

538
00:30:45.312 --> 00:30:48.672
And we got interested in the field of

539
00:30:49.132 --> 00:30:53.072
mutagenesis in normal tissues some years ago, sort of around 2019,

540
00:30:53.132 --> 00:30:56.562
'20, with a local patient in Cambridge who developed

541
00:30:56.772 --> 00:30:59.532
AML after having been treated for neuroblastoma.

542
00:31:00.272 --> 00:31:03.822
And one of the beauties of the National Health Service is that it's very good at

543
00:31:03.832 --> 00:31:07.661
banking stuff, and it's quite relatively easy to get hold of stuff.

544
00:31:08.372 --> 00:31:12.362
And what we tried to do in this trial is then to reconstruct how she's gone from

545
00:31:12.372 --> 00:31:14.512
the beginning of the treatment all the way to leukemia.

546
00:31:14.532 --> 00:31:17.332
And I won't talk to you about all the detail here.

547
00:31:17.372 --> 00:31:18.372
The key thing is this,

548
00:31:19.632 --> 00:31:23.022
one thing that we did find is that halfway through induction treatments, at that

549
00:31:23.052 --> 00:31:26.552
point, this child will have had about half of their platinum treatment.

550
00:31:27.072 --> 00:31:29.372
She had developed two hematopoietic clones.

551
00:31:29.442 --> 00:31:30.832
And it's quite important to

552
00:31:32.012 --> 00:31:35.232
just appreciate at the moment that percentage number there, 1.5%,

553
00:31:35.372 --> 00:31:39.072
7.8%. Those are huge clones in the

554
00:31:39.112 --> 00:31:43.012
clonal hematopoiesis world. And one critical thing here, so this is

555
00:31:43.052 --> 00:31:46.952
normal blood, and the most critical thing to point out here is that there isn't

556
00:31:46.992 --> 00:31:50.912
a driver mutation in there. And because most studies of clonal

557
00:31:50.922 --> 00:31:54.872
hematopoiesis, for cost reasons, will confine themselves to

558
00:31:54.952 --> 00:31:58.372
a few leukemogenic genes, this clonal

559
00:31:58.382 --> 00:32:02.012
hematopoiesis would not have been detected had one done a normal

560
00:32:02.052 --> 00:32:05.972
clonal hematopoiesis study. The only way to find this at that time was to

561
00:32:06.012 --> 00:32:08.952
just sequence the hell out of the samples, which is what we did.

562
00:32:09.612 --> 00:32:13.132
The second thing to say is, and very similar to what you've just heard before, is

563
00:32:13.172 --> 00:32:16.992
that the key driver event in this leukemia, which is a

564
00:32:17.032 --> 00:32:20.752
PDDRN11 mutation, was caused with a near 100%

565
00:32:20.762 --> 00:32:24.732
probability by mutational signatures due to platinum treatment.

566
00:32:26.592 --> 00:32:28.112
In this study, it's a very small paper.

567
00:32:28.172 --> 00:32:31.292
We had one more child, and I'll just mention her because that was quite

568
00:32:31.372 --> 00:32:34.932
fascinating. She had an MLL rearranged leukemia after

569
00:32:34.992 --> 00:32:38.752
neuroblastoma, and MLL rearranged leukemias after cancer treatment

570
00:32:39.232 --> 00:32:42.012
historically have been ascribed to etoposide.

571
00:32:42.492 --> 00:32:46.112
Now, what was quite fascinating in her is that before she had the

572
00:32:46.192 --> 00:32:49.832
MLL rearrangement in her normal blood, she also developed

573
00:32:49.852 --> 00:32:53.692
platinum clonal hematopoiesis and acquired the

574
00:32:53.852 --> 00:32:56.912
MLL mutation on top of the platinum clone.

575
00:32:57.392 --> 00:32:59.042
Now, I could go on about this for ages.

576
00:32:59.112 --> 00:33:02.812
I think that's a fundamental question about that idea about

577
00:33:02.852 --> 00:33:06.252
etoposide and MLL, but I won't take you on that tangent, so

578
00:33:06.712 --> 00:33:09.132
I'll try to stay on track. And then we had one more child.

579
00:33:09.192 --> 00:33:13.112
This is just a handful of children in whom we found clonal hematopoiesis, again,

580
00:33:13.212 --> 00:33:16.892
driverless. She unfortunately died, so we don't know whether she would have

581
00:33:16.932 --> 00:33:18.232
developed AML or not.

582
00:33:19.252 --> 00:33:22.581
So what we learned from that experiment is that platinum-mediated

583
00:33:22.632 --> 00:33:26.272
mutagenesis is also pervasive in children. And of course, it would be.

584
00:33:26.332 --> 00:33:28.622
There's absolutely no reason why it should not be,

585
00:33:29.472 --> 00:33:33.152
but the literature is a little bit confusing, and clones were driverless.

586
00:33:33.852 --> 00:33:37.092
Now, there are two major studies on survivors.

587
00:33:37.172 --> 00:33:39.322
One is this wonderful, wonderful paper from St.

588
00:33:39.432 --> 00:33:42.932
Jude's that we heard about, and another is from MSKCC from Eli

589
00:33:43.012 --> 00:33:46.752
Papayiannis. And in both studies, there wasn't really much

590
00:33:46.832 --> 00:33:50.592
evidence that platinum clonal hematopoiesis exists in

591
00:33:50.652 --> 00:33:53.272
survivors. But this is a technical problem.

592
00:33:53.352 --> 00:33:57.032
So the way these experiments are designed is that if they discover

593
00:33:57.132 --> 00:34:00.912
something, it is definitely there, but if it isn't there, it doesn't

594
00:34:00.952 --> 00:34:03.912
mean that it is there. And I'll try to explain that in a bit more detail.

595
00:34:04.392 --> 00:34:06.212
So what is the technical issue?

596
00:34:07.172 --> 00:34:10.361
Starting with the fertilized egg, so I'm just showing you a fertilized egg here,

597
00:34:10.392 --> 00:34:12.352
and in black are the germline mutations.

598
00:34:13.252 --> 00:34:17.132
As the fertilized egg divides, it acquires mutations,

599
00:34:17.272 --> 00:34:19.832
probably about one substitution per cell division.

600
00:34:20.292 --> 00:34:23.832
So every cell, every normal cell in our body is

601
00:34:23.912 --> 00:34:25.732
riddled with substitutions.

602
00:34:27.672 --> 00:34:31.372
If we were to sequence this normal

603
00:34:31.432 --> 00:34:34.953
tissue now, so imagine this is now a normal tissue composed of millions and

604
00:34:35.013 --> 00:34:38.752
millions of cells, what we would see is there are germline mutations, and the blue

605
00:34:38.852 --> 00:34:41.752
numbers are the cell-specific mutations.

606
00:34:42.352 --> 00:34:46.082
Now, because of how whole genome sequencing or

607
00:34:46.111 --> 00:34:49.892
conventional sequencing works is it doesn't see the mutations in

608
00:34:49.973 --> 00:34:53.432
front of it right now. It sees the mutations of the

609
00:34:53.473 --> 00:34:55.792
cell that the tissue is derived from.

610
00:34:55.832 --> 00:34:59.172
So if I were to do whole genome sequencing on this particular tissue,

611
00:34:59.832 --> 00:35:03.492
all I would see are the black mutations, the germline mutations.

612
00:35:04.072 --> 00:35:04.372
So

613
00:35:05.192 --> 00:35:08.852
cell-specific mutations are entirely invisible to

614
00:35:08.892 --> 00:35:12.812
conventional sequencing, and that then explains-- Oh, hello, Lisa, wonderful to

615
00:35:12.892 --> 00:35:13.191
see you.

616
00:35:14.332 --> 00:35:15.912
Oh, and Mike. Gosh, what a pleasure.

617
00:35:18.572 --> 00:35:22.072
That then explains why we cannot see these mutations.

618
00:35:23.352 --> 00:35:26.952
So what happens when we have got mutagen exposure, such as platinum

619
00:35:27.052 --> 00:35:30.972
chemotherapy? We get damage, and I'm showing you the damage here with these

620
00:35:31.032 --> 00:35:34.712
red letters, and each damage is unique to each

621
00:35:34.732 --> 00:35:38.712
individual cell. So again, if we were to sequence

622
00:35:39.152 --> 00:35:43.052
this piece of normal tissue with the red mutations, we wouldn't see the

623
00:35:43.112 --> 00:35:45.812
red mutations because they're unique to each individual

624
00:35:46.652 --> 00:35:50.072
cell. The only way that we can see them in mother nature

625
00:35:50.632 --> 00:35:53.992
is if there was a clonal expansion, and that's what I'm trying to show here, and

626
00:35:54.032 --> 00:35:57.752
then that cell becomes the dominant clone, and then we could see the

627
00:35:59.432 --> 00:36:01.512
genome of the cell from which this derived from.

628
00:36:01.892 --> 00:36:05.872
So if we get a relapse after platinum exposure, we

629
00:36:05.932 --> 00:36:08.332
will always see platinum mutations.

630
00:36:09.052 --> 00:36:12.992
So what can we do to see them? So we either

631
00:36:13.132 --> 00:36:17.072
need a clonal expansion or we have to make a clonal expansion, which is

632
00:36:17.112 --> 00:36:20.932
incredibly difficult. And in the previous talk, you

633
00:36:21.052 --> 00:36:22.672
just saw this sort of mentioned in a corner.

634
00:36:22.712 --> 00:36:26.352
It's incredibly laborious to take individual cells and to clone

635
00:36:26.412 --> 00:36:29.512
them, and it's not an experiment that is particularly scalable.

636
00:36:29.552 --> 00:36:31.152
And Ruben will probably show you some data.

637
00:36:31.162 --> 00:36:33.052
He's done some phenomenal work in that field.

638
00:36:33.572 --> 00:36:37.352
And then the other option is to do single-cell DNA sequencing, which a few

639
00:36:37.412 --> 00:36:41.212
years wasn't really possible at base pair resolution that was sort of

640
00:36:41.412 --> 00:36:44.852
high enough quality to call mutations. But now it probably is.

641
00:36:44.872 --> 00:36:46.312
And are you going to show us some data?

642
00:36:46.392 --> 00:36:50.364
Wonderful.And then there is another way around to

643
00:36:50.884 --> 00:36:54.544
get to the tissues in the normal mutations. That's called duplex sequencing.

644
00:36:54.604 --> 00:36:57.074
It's a technology that's been around for many, many years.

645
00:36:57.124 --> 00:36:58.384
There are different implementations.

646
00:36:58.424 --> 00:37:02.324
The implementation at Sanger is called nanosequencing, which was developed by Inigo

647
00:37:02.364 --> 00:37:06.043
Martincorena. It's an incredibly powerful method that builds on the

648
00:37:06.084 --> 00:37:09.744
following principle. So what I'm showing you here is a molecule of

649
00:37:09.764 --> 00:37:13.554
DNA, and on this end here, you see an artifact, and

650
00:37:13.844 --> 00:37:17.404
so this artifact is a mutant base. But what is different

651
00:37:18.044 --> 00:37:22.004
between this artifact and this real mutation here is that this one

652
00:37:22.024 --> 00:37:25.504
is present in one strand, whereas this one here is present in both strands.

653
00:37:25.964 --> 00:37:29.744
So the principle of duplex sequencing, therefore, is to tag

654
00:37:29.944 --> 00:37:33.764
each individual strand of DNA, and then what we can do is we can

655
00:37:33.844 --> 00:37:37.404
call mutations on each strand individually and ask the question: Do we see it on

656
00:37:37.544 --> 00:37:41.424
both or just on one? And what that does is

657
00:37:41.464 --> 00:37:44.784
it ramps up the specificity of mutation calling to an

658
00:37:44.844 --> 00:37:48.684
incredible, incredible fidelity, such that we can

659
00:37:48.724 --> 00:37:52.384
now call mutations in individual molecules of DNA, and

660
00:37:52.463 --> 00:37:55.464
thus we can interrogate normal tissues.

661
00:37:55.524 --> 00:37:58.914
The advantage of nanosequencing are the difference.

662
00:37:59.014 --> 00:38:00.024
It's not necessarily an advantage.

663
00:38:00.064 --> 00:38:03.624
It's a different kind of experiment, but what it allows us to do is to

664
00:38:03.644 --> 00:38:05.134
interrogate just normal tissues.

665
00:38:05.204 --> 00:38:08.824
We don't have to clone individual cells, and we haven't got the expense

666
00:38:08.964 --> 00:38:12.464
of whole-genome DNA sequencing. We can interrogate

667
00:38:12.644 --> 00:38:15.264
millions and millions of cells in one experiment.

668
00:38:17.044 --> 00:38:20.684
So the experiment that I'm going to do, I just need to acknowledge two people.

669
00:38:20.764 --> 00:38:23.144
One is Anna Wenger, who was a postdoc in my lab.

670
00:38:23.164 --> 00:38:26.584
She's now a group leader in her home country in Sweden at the University of

671
00:38:26.624 --> 00:38:28.464
Gothenburg, and the other is Fuad Rouhani.

672
00:38:28.484 --> 00:38:30.904
Fuad is a transplant surgeon at King's College London.

673
00:38:31.304 --> 00:38:34.994
King's College is one of those motherships, the birthplace of modern hepatology,

674
00:38:35.524 --> 00:38:38.084
and he's also a group lead at the Francis Crick Institute.

675
00:38:38.094 --> 00:38:41.544
And really, without him, we wouldn't have been able to do this experiment.

676
00:38:43.584 --> 00:38:47.274
So what we decided to do is, let's look at

677
00:38:47.724 --> 00:38:47.734
a

678
00:38:48.664 --> 00:38:52.564
solid normal organ rather than blood, and then what organ would we

679
00:38:52.604 --> 00:38:56.483
look at? So if we think about our practice, there aren't many tumor

680
00:38:56.524 --> 00:38:58.464
types where we would get an entire organ.

681
00:38:58.483 --> 00:39:02.304
We'd get kidneys, we'd get livers, and that's about it.

682
00:39:02.384 --> 00:39:06.124
One might get a little bit of normal tissue around other tumor types, for most

683
00:39:06.164 --> 00:39:09.724
really, the only two tumor types that I can think of are liver

684
00:39:09.744 --> 00:39:13.624
and kidney. Now, the problem, or not the

685
00:39:13.664 --> 00:39:17.264
problem, the issue with kidney tumors is that, of course, we don't pretreat them

686
00:39:17.304 --> 00:39:20.904
with platinum agents. When we do give chemotherapy, it's usually

687
00:39:20.964 --> 00:39:22.574
non-platinum-based chemotherapy.

688
00:39:22.984 --> 00:39:26.464
So liver tumors, hepatoblastoma, the most common type of

689
00:39:26.744 --> 00:39:30.684
children's liver cancer, was an ideal case for what we wanted to do

690
00:39:30.744 --> 00:39:34.484
is because these children get pretreated with platinum agents, either

691
00:39:34.604 --> 00:39:38.243
one or two, and then some children have got whole liver resection.

692
00:39:38.304 --> 00:39:40.104
It's those children that we targeted.

693
00:39:40.493 --> 00:39:44.484
We work very closely with the pathologists, who very kindly then slice the

694
00:39:44.524 --> 00:39:47.444
liver for us, and I apologize for this rather unpalatable picture.

695
00:39:47.844 --> 00:39:49.324
And what we did is we took multiple

696
00:39:50.564 --> 00:39:53.284
normal liver biopsies of these livers.

697
00:39:54.084 --> 00:39:57.784
And this is to give you sort of an overview of the

698
00:39:58.084 --> 00:40:01.544
scale of the experiment. In total, we looked at 155 liver

699
00:40:01.564 --> 00:40:05.164
biopsies plus some other tissues, and these liver biopsies

700
00:40:05.204 --> 00:40:09.154
importantly included treated liver biopsies, untreated with

701
00:40:09.164 --> 00:40:12.284
cisplatin, cisplatin and carboplatin, with or without SDS.

702
00:40:12.344 --> 00:40:15.484
And the reason why I mention SDS is as follows.

703
00:40:15.584 --> 00:40:19.344
SDS is a chelating agent which we use in hepatoblastoma treatment to prevent

704
00:40:19.424 --> 00:40:23.384
ototoxicity, and we had just a little bit of a concern that maybe

705
00:40:23.424 --> 00:40:27.064
that's going to interfere with what we will see, and therefore, we tried very hard

706
00:40:27.104 --> 00:40:30.144
to target children who had cisplatin without SDS.

707
00:40:30.184 --> 00:40:33.964
We also have got non-hepatoblastoma liver tissue and other tissues.

708
00:40:34.004 --> 00:40:37.924
So it's quite a vast experiment. And we divided it into two parts, a

709
00:40:37.944 --> 00:40:41.784
discovery study for the sample here, and then a validation study where we

710
00:40:41.824 --> 00:40:44.354
re-interrogated the previous samples and added more.

711
00:40:47.084 --> 00:40:49.474
So the data in the discovery cohort.

712
00:40:50.204 --> 00:40:53.984
The first finding is this. So what I'm showing you here is interrogating the

713
00:40:54.044 --> 00:40:57.924
normal tissues, blood, normal liver, and liver tumors

714
00:40:58.504 --> 00:41:00.624
by conventional whole genome sequencing.

715
00:41:00.654 --> 00:41:04.234
And as I explained to you before, we would expect to see a lot of

716
00:41:04.264 --> 00:41:07.864
mutations in liver tumors because the readout is the

717
00:41:07.944 --> 00:41:11.784
most common ancestor of the tumor, whereas in the normal tissue,

718
00:41:11.864 --> 00:41:15.784
we see barely any mutations. We see germline mutations, but we barely see

719
00:41:15.824 --> 00:41:19.264
any somatic mutations, and the mutations that we see are sort

720
00:41:19.404 --> 00:41:22.724
of mutations of the first or second cell divisions, so

721
00:41:22.824 --> 00:41:25.184
postzygotic mutations with a very high VAF.

722
00:41:25.684 --> 00:41:29.603
This is a log scale here, and we've also plotted what one would expect to see in

723
00:41:29.664 --> 00:41:32.804
normal adult blood and in normal adult livers.

724
00:41:33.754 --> 00:41:36.944
And this is now what whole-genome nanosequencing shows, and it's quite dramatic.

725
00:41:37.464 --> 00:41:41.064
So we can see that the mutation burden of children exposed to

726
00:41:41.084 --> 00:41:44.884
platinum in black is elevated to that what we

727
00:41:44.944 --> 00:41:47.644
would see in adults, and the same is true for the liver.

728
00:41:47.674 --> 00:41:51.604
And of course, the mutation burden of the tumors barely changes because

729
00:41:51.644 --> 00:41:55.264
we already have got a clonal readout, and it just adds a few extra

730
00:41:55.324 --> 00:41:57.344
mutations that we wouldn't have seen.

731
00:41:57.364 --> 00:42:01.324
And also note, this experiment gives us a sense of what is the

732
00:42:01.344 --> 00:42:05.204
normal mutation burden in children's blood and in children's

733
00:42:05.264 --> 00:42:08.604
normal liver, and it sits here about wherever it is, one to

734
00:42:08.804 --> 00:42:12.784
200. So I hope I can show you just how dramatic this technology

735
00:42:12.844 --> 00:42:16.524
is in revealing that hidden universe of normal tissue mutations.

736
00:42:17.424 --> 00:42:21.144
Then the next thing, and this is a thing that we sort of didn't expect to find, and

737
00:42:21.244 --> 00:42:25.024
it took us quite a long time to accept that this really is

738
00:42:25.044 --> 00:42:28.904
true, is that in liver, there was a

739
00:42:29.104 --> 00:42:33.024
novel and liver-specific mutational signature of platinum

740
00:42:33.064 --> 00:42:36.024
exposure. So you've seen these plots in the previous talks.

741
00:42:36.144 --> 00:42:38.364
I won't go through them in great detail.

742
00:42:38.424 --> 00:42:41.404
On the x-axis, we've got all the different mutations in their

743
00:42:42.044 --> 00:42:45.964
trinucleotide context, so the base before and after.

744
00:42:46.464 --> 00:42:48.584
On the y-axis is the mutation burden.

745
00:42:49.004 --> 00:42:52.224
You can ignore this, you can ignore that, and these down here, these are known

746
00:42:52.284 --> 00:42:56.084
platinum signatures that we just plotted so you get a sense of what do

747
00:42:56.164 --> 00:42:58.464
normal platinum signatures look like.

748
00:42:58.884 --> 00:43:02.748
And what we see in the liver is this very different pattern.We've used

749
00:43:02.788 --> 00:43:06.148
two different ways to extract this, and then the other thing that these

750
00:43:06.208 --> 00:43:09.848
algorithms do is they sort of put a number to how confident the

751
00:43:09.908 --> 00:43:13.648
algorithm is in the result, and this is called confidence with

752
00:43:13.688 --> 00:43:17.208
this and stability in that, and in both cases, the confidence is

753
00:43:17.268 --> 00:43:21.228
incredibly high. So this is as true as it gets in the space

754
00:43:21.288 --> 00:43:22.628
of mutational signatures.

755
00:43:24.408 --> 00:43:26.048
Now let's validate and extend that.

756
00:43:26.108 --> 00:43:29.988
So the first thing that we did is we looked at all published data, and a huge

757
00:43:30.048 --> 00:43:33.188
thank you to a bunch of people who provided their data, and particularly Adam

